column24: The rest of NT defers to the policy of the NT state government.  Measures are not taken to close workplaces. However, all businesses are required to lodge a COVID-19 Safety Plan that must be complied with and reviewed every six months to ensure any required safety responsibilities are addressed. column33: The rest of NT defers to the policy of the NT state government.  Policies are still not taken to cancel public events. However, in major population centres, events with more than 500 people require the submission of a COVID-19 Small Event Checklist and the appointment of a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and displaying a QR code or alternate method of checking in, while events with more than 1000 people require submission of a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan and formal approval from the Chief Health officer, as well as appointment of a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and displaying a QR code or alternate method of checking in. Outside of major population centres, events with more than 100 people require the submission of a COVID-19 Small Event Checklist and the appointment of a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and display a QR code or alternate method of checking in, while events with more than 500 people require submission of a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan and formal approval from the Chief Health officer, as well as appointment of a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and displaying a QR code or alternate method of checking in.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120165651/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings

column60: The rest of NT defers to the policy of the NT state government.  Several regions within NT were under lockdown during this period.  During a lockdown, residents must stay at home and are only permitted to leave for medical treatment, essential goods and services (once per day), essential work (1 hr per day), exercise, providing care and support to someone who cannot support themselves, and emergencies.  The Wessel Islands Archipelago, encompassing Elcho Island including Galiwin’ku and Wessel Island including Martjanba, remain in lockdown, with the end date set at 30 January 2022.  Gunyangara (Ski Beach), Utopia Homelands and Wurrumiyanga entered lockdown from 22 January 2022 to 29 January 2022.  Alice Springs, Amoonguna, Yuendumu, and Yuelamu remain in lockout, during which vaccinated people may live normally within the lockout area, but unvaccinated people are only permitted to leave their homes for medical treatment, essential goods and services, exercise (1 hr per day), providing care and support to someone who cannot support themselves, and emergencies.  Milikapiti entered a lockdown at 3pm on 24 January 2022, set to finish at 2pm 30 January 2022.  Ampilatwatja entered a 48 hour lockdown at 2pm on 28 January 2022.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220130074104/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129102123/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/hotspots-and-case-locations/nt  https://web.archive.org/web/20220205025033/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/updates/items/2022-01-24-nt-covid-19-update-milikapiti-enters-72-hour-lockdown
column69: The rest of NT defers to the policy of the NT state government. column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travelers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).     The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.     The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.     A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.     The directions in place between on the 22 Janurary to 30 Janurary were a continuation of existing directions. column115: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as of 30 January 2022), the elderly were advised to reduce their risk of falling ill from COVID-19 by practicing good personal hygiene and physical distancing, getting vaccinated, as well as arranging for medications, groceries and other essential items to be delivered to them.    The Federal Government also supported initiatives to assist the elderly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The elderly could access home care packages, contact their aged care service providers to gain simplified access to urgent services, and the Commonwealth Home Support Program (CHSP) enabled the elderly to access emergency support to live with relatives during the pandemic. Frameworks for mandatory aged care worker vaccination were also applied across the country. Nonetheless, State and Territory Governments were generally responsible for setting aged care mandates in their own jurisdictions. The directions in place between 22-30 January were a continuation of existing directions.  Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220130014251/https://www.health.gov.au/node/18602/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-older-people-and-carers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220122173147/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-older-australians-faqs  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214222122/https://www.health.gov.au/health-topics/aged-care/advice-on-aged-care-during-covid-19/managing-home-care  https://web.archive.org/web/20220128074317/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines/mandatory-covid-19-vaccination-in-aged-care

column88: According to the information published on the Prime Minister of Australia website on 05 Jan 2022, testing will not be required before patients present to hospital. Confirmation PCR test will not be required after a positive RAT. Individual states and territories will provide further information on how a positive RAT will be recorded. Anyone who tests positive is encouraged to contact their GP for support as required. Testing before interstate travel will no longer be required except for Queensland, Tasmania and Western Australia, with Queensland and Tasmania to review these requirements in the coming weeks. column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).     The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.     The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.     A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.     The directions in place between on the 22 Janurary to 30 Janurary were a continuation of existing directions. column115: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as of 30 January 2022), the elderly were advised to reduce their risk of falling ill from COVID-19 by practicing good personal hygiene and physical distancing, getting vaccinated, as well as arranging for medications, groceries and other essential items to be delivered to them.    The Federal Government also supported initiatives to assist the elderly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The elderly could access home care packages, contact their aged care service providers to gain simplified access to urgent services, and the Commonwealth Home Support Program (CHSP) enabled the elderly to access emergency support to live with relatives during the pandemic. Frameworks for mandatory aged care worker vaccination were also applied across the country. Nonetheless, State and Territory Governments were generally responsible for setting aged care mandates in their own jurisdictions. The directions in place between 22-30 January were a continuation of existing directions. column15: According to the Department of Education, Skills and Employment website (as last updated on 24 January 2022 and current as of 13 February 2022), State and Territory Governments, as well as relevant authorities outside of the Government, would be responsible for all operational decisions pertaining to schools.     Nonetheless, there was the expectation that Australian schools would open in 2022 and continue to follow official health advice. The National Cabinet established The National Framework for Managing COVID-19 in Schools and Early Childhood Education Centres (ECEC) on 13 January 2022 to promote a nationally consistent approach to managing school operations during COVID-19.  This framework encouraged the adoption of multilayered prevention strategies (such as a combination of mask wearing, hygiene practices, physical distancing, or ventilation) in schools to keep staff and students safe, although it was up to relevant authorities in each jurisdiction to decide how COVID-safe measures would be implemented.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).    The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.    The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.    A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column106: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as last updated 3 February 2022), the Australian Government had been distributing COVID-19 vaccines through Operation COVID Shield, the national taskforce coordinating the Australian vaccine rollout.    As part of the rollout, all Australians* aged 5 years and over could book a free COVID-19 vaccination appointment, although it was slightly more difficult for those in the 5-11 year age group to receive a vaccine compared to other eligible age groups, as not all vaccine providers were able to provide the smaller Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine dose for 5-11 year olds.    The Pfizer (Comirnaty) COVID-19 vaccine was available for individuals aged 5 years and above, the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 vaccine was available to individuals aged 60 years and above (or 18-59 year olds who had chosen to take the vaccine after consulting with a healthcare professional), and the Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccine was available to individuals 12 years and above. The Novavax (Nuvaxovid) COVID-19 vaccine was also available to those aged 18 years old and above after being provisionally approved by the TGA on 20 January 2022.    Booster vaccines were available for individuals aged 16 years and above who had completed their primary course of COVID-19 vaccination at least 3 months ago. 16-17 year olds could take the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine as part of their booster dose, and those aged 18 years and above could either take the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine or the Pfizer COVID-19 for their booster shot.    Immunocompromised individuals could also take a third primary dose of a COVID-19 vaccine.    As 93.65% of Australians aged 16 years and above had received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 77.11% of Australians aged 12-15 years old had received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, and 44.15% of Australians aged 5-11 years old had received at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, the Australian Government was likely able to deliver on its universal vaccination policy. Nonetheless, State and Territory Governments also delivered their own updates and specialised services to meet the needs of their jurisdictions.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions.      *For the purposes of the vaccine rollout, Australian = those living in Australia    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214115310/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/about-rollout  https://web.archive.org/web/20220126100654/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-your-vaccination/locations  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129073055/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated  https://web.archive.org/web/20220201192548/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated/children  https://web.archive.org/web/20220201022840/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-your-vaccination/booster-doses  https://web.archive.org/web/20220131131114/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/approved-vaccines/novavax  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214120409/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2022/02/covid-19-vaccine-rollout-update-5-february-2022.pdf

The Federal Government also supported initiatives to assist the elderly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The elderly could access home care packages, contact their aged care service providers to gain simplified access to urgent services, and the Commonwealth Home Support Program (CHSP) enabled the elderly to access emergency support to live with relatives during the pandemic. column115: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as of 30 January 2022), the elderly were advised to reduce their risk of falling ill from COVID-19 by practicing good personal hygiene and physical distancing, getting vaccinated, as well as arranging for medications, groceries and other essential items to be delivered to them.    The Federal Government also supported initiatives to assist the elderly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The elderly could access home care packages, contact their aged care service providers to gain simplified access to urgent services, and the Commonwealth Home Support Program (CHSP) enabled the elderly to access emergency support to live with relatives during the pandemic. Frameworks for mandatory aged care worker vaccination were also applied across the country. Nonetheless, State and Territory Governments were generally responsible for setting aged care mandates in their own jurisdictions.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column15: As of 21 February 2022, there is no vaccination requirement/mandatory for students to attend and access schools in Australia.  On 10 February 2022, Health Department of Australian Government published a statement: "Is it true? Are COVID-19 vaccines mandatory in Australia?" The Covid-19 vaccine is voluntary as are all vaccinations in Australia and people maintain the option to choose.  There may be circumstances in the future in which proof of vaccination will be required, such as border or re-entry requirements, or continued employment in particular areas. One example of this is the mandatory vaccination requirements for all residential aged care workers which will come into effect on 17 September 2021 in line with relevant state and territory directions. column15: As of 8 March 2022, there is no vaccination requirement/mandatory for students to attend and access schools in Australia.  On 10 February 2022, Health Department of Australian Government published a statement: "Is it true? Are COVID-19 vaccines mandatory in Australia?" The Covid-19 vaccine is voluntary as are all vaccinations in Australia and people maintain the option to choose.  There may be circumstances in the future in which proof of vaccination will be required, such as border or re-entry requirements, or continued employment in particular areas. One example of this is the mandatory vaccination requirements for all residential aged care workers which will come into effect on 17 September 2021 in line with relevant state and territory directions.  Face masks, social distancing, and check-in application requirements are under the jurisdiction of every state in Australia.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220215170701/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/is-it-true/is-it-true-are-covid-19-vaccines-mandatory-in-australia   https://web.archive.org/web/20220227020250/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-02-25/covid-mask-rules-australian-states-territories/100854564
column24: As of 8 March 2022, there is no national vaccination requirement/mandatory for business attendees or visitors, thus, visitors' proof of vaccination requirements is under the jurisdiction of every state in Australia.  On the other hand, on 27 May 2020, Fair Work Ombudsman published "Protecting employees and customers" that has been updated on 23 September 2021 that the policy requires employers to create a safe work environment. It is a legal requirement.  Face masks, social distancing, and check-in application requirements is also under the jurisdiction of every state in Australia.   This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220311065914/https://coronavirus.fairwork.gov.au/coronavirus-and-australian-workplace-laws/health-and-safety-in-the-workplace/protecting-employees-and-customers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220227020250/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-02-25/covid-mask-rules-australian-states-territories/100854564

column74: As of 8 March 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: As of 8 March 2022, the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   According to the Services Australia website, eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19 or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19). For more details see the archive link below.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214022140/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment?context=60352 https://web.archive.org/web/20220214022312/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-western-australia-you-can-get?context=53218

column115: As of 8 March 2022, the Commonwealth Government is encouraging visitors to aged care facility to get Covid-19 vaccines. column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work. column15: "As at 20th April 2022, the federal government did not specifically impose any requirements or restrictions on schools or other education places. However, on 13 January 2022, the National Cabinet (federal government) established a framework to ensure that the education system across Australia is consistent in managing COVID-19. Namely, this framework established   - early childhood education services and schools are essential and should be the first to open and the last to close wherever possible in outbreak situations, with face-to-face learning prioritised  - Baseline public health measures continue to apply  - No vulnerable child or child of an essential worker is turned away  - Responses to be proportionate and health risk-based  - Equip early childhood education services and schools to respond on the basis of public health advice and with support from public health authorities where required  -Wellbeing of children and education staff to be supported.  However, the state and territory governments are responsible for determining  what this means for their state/territory. This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420001617/https://www.dese.gov.au/covid-19/schools "

column74: "As at 20 April 2022, vaccinated Australians and permanent residents  can travel in and out of Australia. Other travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Proof of vaccination can take the form of   - If you are vaccinated, you must present your COVID-19 vaccination certificate to the airline staff when checking-in for your travel.  -If vaccinated in Australia, you can get your International COVID-19 Vaccination Certificate (ICVC) from the MyGov portal. If in Australia but vaccinated overseas, you may be able to access an ICVC if you have been vaccinated with a vaccine approved or recognised by the TGA.You will need to present your ICVC, or other proof of vaccination, when you check-in for your flight to or from Australia.  For international travellers, they must present a certificate.  Non-vaccinated travellers must have an exemption or medical contraindication (e.g. cannot be vaccinated)  This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel"
column77: "As at 20 April 2022, there is a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment available. This is equivalent to less than 50% of an individuals income. This is available only to formally employed workers. It is a continuance of the policy.   The payment is available to:  - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  -you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.  The person must have also met the following requirements:   -you’ve lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work  -you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for. column15: There are no requirements set by the national government on school closures or alterations to services. The National Framework for Managing COVID-19 in Schools and Early Childhood Education and Care introduced on 13th Jan 2022 contains guiding principles and objectives for national consistency, but the specific measures taken to adhere to this framework will be implemented by the state and territory governements.     Some of the principles outlined in the framework include:    - Strongly encouraging, but not requiring, vaccination of all eligible persons   - Practice and promotion of evidence based COVID-Safe behaviours at all times, irrespective of the level of COVID-19 community transmission  - Adoption of a multilayered prevention strategy   - Persons must stay at home if experiencing COVID-19 symptoms or if required to isolate in line with the jurisdiction’s health advice      Link: https://archive.ph/OPvLp

column74: In continuation with existing policy, beginning on 18 April 2022:  - to travel into and out of Australia travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Unvaccinated travellers may have their visa cancelled and be detained and removed if they do not have a medical contraindication to a COVID-19 vaccine as defined by the Australian Government; or are not in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption. Unnvaccinated travellers are advised that in some states and territories they may need to enter quarantine.  - travellers must declare critical health information;   > all travellers arriving by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration (excluding flight crew)  > all travellers arriving on a cruise vessel must complete a Maritime Travel Declaration   - you do not need to take a COVID-19 test that is negative to enter Australia  - masks must be worn on flgiths to Australia by adults (older than 11 years), excluding individuals with a medical certificate and individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing (and their contacts) who require seeing the whole face for communication.  - travellers are advised to check testing and quarantine requirements and domestic transfer restrictions for state and territories. column77: In continuation with existing policy, the national government provides the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for individuals who have lost work due to self-isolation or quarantine as required by state or territory governments, or caring responsibilities, due to COVID-19. To be eligible individuals must meet criteria on amount of work lost, limits on liquid assets, other leave entitlements, age, visa/citizenship, timing.    ""Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to:    - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  - you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.    You must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible:    - you’re unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring  - you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  - you have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - you’re at least 17 years old and live in Australia  - you’re an Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - Your isolation or caring period must begin on or before 30 June 2022.    For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, we’ll pay you:    - $450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://archive.ph/4KJoW (Last updated 29 April 2022)

column15: On 13 January 2022, National Cabinet agreed to a national framework to promote a nationally consistent approach to the ongoing delivery of high-quality education for all students during COVID-19.    The National Framework for Managing COVID-19 in Schools and Early Childhood Education and Care (ECEC) (the Framework) aims to ensure all schools and ECEC are open and be able to stay open, with as little disruption from COVID-19 as possible.    The Framework is based on six national guiding principles:    ECEC services and schools are essential and should be the first to open and the last to close wherever possible in outbreak situations, with face-to-face learning prioritised  Baseline public health measures continue to apply  No vulnerable child or child of an essential worker is turned away  Responses to be proportionate and health risk-based  Equip ECEC services and schools to respond on the basis of public health advice and with support from public health authorities where required  Wellbeing of children and education staff to be supported.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601104406/https://www.dese.gov.au/covid-19/schools
column24: There are no current workplace restrictions. However, to maintain the safety of all workers and visitors, employers must consider physical or social distancing, cleaning and hygiene as well as risk assessments. Employers also have a duty to consult workers regarding COVID-19 risks and how these risks are to be managed. This includes the introduction of workplace policies relating to vaccination.   	- ensuring your workers do not come to work when unwell,   	- ensuring your workers do not come to work if they have tested positive for COVID-19 unless they have been released from isolation by the relevant public health authority,  	- ensuring physical distancing in the workplace and adhering to density limits (check occupancy limits for the type of building and building standards).   	For example:  	- supporting workers to work from home or relocating work tasks to different areas of the workplace or off-site,   	- staggering your workers’ start, finish and break times,   	- reducing the number of situations where workers come into close contact, for example in lunchrooms and other shared spaces  	  	  https://web.archive.org/web/20220601105157/https://covid19.swa.gov.au/covid-19-information-workplaces/industry-information/office/vaccination

""Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to:    - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  - you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.    You must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible:    - you’re unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring  - you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  - you have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - you’re at least 17 years old and live in Australia  - you’re an Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - Your isolation or caring period must begin on or before 30 June 2022.    For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, we’ll pay you:    - $450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://archive.ph/4KJoW
column79: In continuation with existing policy, there is no debt or contract relief provided by the national government.    https://archive.ph/f1ZMK
column86: The Australian Government Department of Health provides  Covid-19 information and regular updates on case numbers and statistics through their website.      https://archive.ph/wZxy6
column88: In continuation with existing policy, the Australian Government advises anyone with COVID-19 symptoms, close contacts of positive cases or if advised to by a health professional to get tested at COVID-19 testing clinics. From 24 Jan 2022, free Rapid Antigen Tests are available to anyone with a Commonwealth concession card - up to 10 RATs over 3 months (maximum 5 per month) - at community pharmacies. Individuals are advised to check state information on testing sites.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220511033053/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/testing
column90: The Australian Government Department of Health advises individuals who test positive to refer to state and territory health authorities for information. There is no federal contact tracing in place.     https://archive.ph/t4Zb5
column103: There are no requirements to wear face masks imposed by the federal government. The Department of Health states that "Restrictions, such as lockdowns, are managed by the states and territories."  They advise checking state or territory information to check any restrictions that are in place.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601112200/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/face-masks-how-they-protect-you
column106: In a continuation of existing policy, vaccinations are available to everyone over 5 years old in Australia. The available vaccines are Vaxzevria (AstraZeneca), Comirnaty (Pfizer), Spikevax (Moderna) and Nuvaxovid (Novavax).    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601113212/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/covid-19-vaccination-vaccine-dose-policy
column115: Recommendations regarding visitors and management of aged care facilities in response to Covid-19 are provided but implemented by state and territory governments.     https://archive.ph/15t7n
